{
  "answer": "The opening ghazal cataloguing divine self-manifestation across opposites appears in **Chapter 1** (\"Chamak teri ayaan bijli mein, aatish mein, sharare mein\") of *Bang-E-Dara Part 2* by Allama Iqbal. It opens with the following couplets (quoted from the English translation):\n\n> Your height in the heavens, Your lowliness in the earth's deep core,[^1]  \n> Your current in the ocean, Your stillness on the waiting shore.  \n>   \n> What is awake in the conscious soul sleeps a slumber deep and far,[^2]  \n> In the tree, the flower, the beast, the stone, and in the distant star.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/01-chamak-teri-ayaan-bijli-mein-aatish-mein-sharare-m/translation/#p-47b71d).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/01-chamak-teri-ayaan-bijli-mein-aatish-mein-sharare-m/translation/#p-efb428).",
